{"key":"post-20177602","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>20177602</id>\n<content>If they're hard and dry, your problem was insufficient substrate moisture content.&amp;nbsp; Don't feel just because you're following a 'tek' that you can't water or even flood the substrate when necessary.&amp;nbsp; Often, pouring a gallon or so of water around the edges of the substrate will cause the fruits to double in size overnight.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Bear in mind, a too-wet substrate will also produce small fruits, but they'll be heavy, soggy and soft.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>20177868</next>\n<prev>20177489</prev>\n<first>20176873</first>\n<last>20188272</last>\n<when>1403613211</when>\n<utime>06/24/14 03:33 PM</utime>\n</post>"}